modules.description: This module implements an HTTP server for handling GitHub webhook requests, providing functions to construct responses with custom status codes, headers, and bodies. It supports request routing through callback functions that process incoming connections, parse request data, and return appropriate responses, including specialized actions like redirects, authentication challenges, and file-based responses. Key data types include connection metadata, HTTP requests and responses, and body streams, with operations tailored for handling webhook payloads and authentication flows.

This module provides a type `t` representing timestamps and two functions: `min`, which returns the minimum possible timestamp, and `now`, which retrieves the current timestamp. It works with time values to support temporal comparisons and logging. Concrete use cases include tracking event times and measuring durations in system operations.

This module implements a Unix-based GitHub webhook handler that manages repository event subscriptions and dispatches callbacks. It works with GitHub tokens, URIs, and event types to register and monitor repositories, supporting operations like adding repos, specifying event types, and clearing subscriptions. Concrete use cases include building CI systems that react to GitHub push events or automating deployment pipelines triggered by repository changes.

This module provides timestamp management with minimum and current time retrieval, an HTTP server implementation for handling GitHub webhook requests with response construction and routing, and a Unix-based handler for managing GitHub repository subscriptions and event callbacks. It operates on time values, HTTP connections and requests, GitHub tokens and URIs, and repository event types. Use cases include logging event timestamps, serving webhook endpoints, and automating CI pipelines triggered by GitHub repository changes.
